segments.text: You can remember only maybe two or three.
We had a guy named Rodney Gott, whose father was president of I think the American Foundry or something like that.
And he used to come up in a great big long Cadillac.
And we had maybe two or three others that
that were in that category, but otherwise why you had individuals who were from the coal mines of West Virginia and who hadn't even had graduated from high school.
Really?
You had some students who were your colleagues that hadn't graduated from high school?
They'd gone to one of these prep schools.
Oh, I see.
Prep to be able to
pass exams, Joe Remus.
And of course, he worked all the time.
I mean, he studied all the time.
But he got through.
And Tom Kilday was another one from Texas.
And then we had another classmate from Bonham, Texas.
and then we had Cam Longley from a little small town up in West Texas.
So, other than the people were from the northeast, why, and you, see you didn't have any fraternization with these people because see, when you entered the military academy in July in 29,
the first time that you were permitted to get a leave was 18 months later.
I mean, you had a Christmas vacation, and then after your sophomore year, between your sophomore year and your junior year, you came home.
I came to Texas.
That was the only time I came back to Texas.
During the time, and then your parents don't come up.
I mean, it's too expensive to come up.
And most of these people, you never see your parents.
And so you don't,

you don't associate an individual that he's a son of a millionaire or, because you never, you wear the same clothes, you have the same allowances, you can't, they're not supposed to give you any money, and you're supposed to earn all, you have a bank account type of thing, and you buy your books and your clothing,
and get your cadet store type of activities all out of your own little bank account.
You just wrote checks for these things.
So everybody was treated exactly the same.
Did you like that aspect of your education?
I was for that because I didn't have to worry about finances.
No, I mean the fact that everybody was treated the same.
Well, you didn't really think about it.
I mean, I don't think you really gave it a lot of thought.
You just accepted it.
You just accepted it.
And you didn't object to it.
I mean, that's the way it was.
If you want to stay there, that's where you abide by the rules and regulations.
And as far as standing in conduct, I guess I was a complier type.
I mean, I wasn't the one that was
not, didn't comply with the regulations.
Whatever the regulations were, that was for me.
Now you talked about at A&M Corps, there was a Spreedy Corps, was that same feeling, that same spirit at West Point?
Yeah, oh yeah.
In larger or less dose, or could you compare it?
Oh, I would say certainly about equal.

And of course, I think that the cadet who goes to Texas A&M, who spends four years there and gets to know all of his classmates, I think he gets the same outlook, the same suite of core as you do at the military academy.
And the fact that you know everybody, you know the people who are playing football,
And I played football.
You played football at West Point?
Oh, yeah.
I was on about the third team.
I passed.
I caught half.
You were an end?
I was an end.
I sat on the seat on the bench before 110,000 in Soldier's Field.
I caught passes between halves.
Oh, you'd get in the game before you got 50 ahead or something of that sort.
And...
And I was on the boxing team, and I played lacrosse.
Were sports emphasized at West Point?
Well, football, yes.
I would say that football, I would say your first team at that time in football were individuals who had already made a name for themselves at some college, like Chris Cagle,
Some of them were all Americans before they went to military academy.
So football, but basketball, boxing, fencing, swimming, there are certain things that you had to do.
You had to learn how to swim.
So there's certain types of athletes you had to learn how to fence.
You also had to learn how to box.
And there's certain intramural athletes that you had to participate in and become proficient in.
Why fencing?
Well, it's one of these, I guess, graceful skills that you
that you participate in.
That was one of the programs that you had to take sometime during your four year period.
Now, here is a Texan from a small town who had never been out of Texas before arriving
on the Hudson River in New York.
What were your impressions of New England?
Well, I met Tom Kilday.
He was from San Antonio, I think.
So I'd gotten in touch with him, and I'd met him at Franklin, Texas, and I boarded the same train that he
He had already been four years in college.
He did?
Yeah, he had already been.
He had graduated from St. Edward's before he had gone to military academy.
So I met him there and we went to St. Louis and then St. Louis to New York and spent the night in New York and then caught the train up from New York.
I had him to follow around and we didn't tarry anywhere until we got to the military cabin.
Of course you were met at the station and by the time you got up on the military reservation there was a bunch of cadets around you making you pick up your baggage, drop it, pick it up, drop it.
this type of thing.
They started from there to indoctrinate you to obey commands.
I don't know.
Did you like New England versus Texas?
Well, New England is a very puritano type of country.
I mean, it's a really pretty country, particularly in the fall, particularly in the springtime.
And, of course, we went up there in July.
And it, of course, was pretty at the time.
I don't really have any thoughts as far as leaving.
I'd say the train ride from Reagan, Texas to Tyler was a lot more impressive because that's the first time you'd ever been away from home.
And you really had to spend very many nights away from home.
Sure.
And getting on a train with, you remember that type of thing.
But as far as the train ride from Texas to West Point, really I don't remember too much about it.
Okay, now let's talk for a minute about the, after you graduated from West Point and received your commission as the second lieutenant,
and later on in your military career, what was your opinion as a West Point graduate of the commissioned officers who had received their training from Texas A&M?
Well, there's been a lot of comment, I'd say, that the West Pointers were
were stuck up and always got the best jobs.
Yeah, I heard that quite a bit.
I don't really think that that is true in the Air Force.
When I graduated from the Military Academy, I ranked 66 out of 346.
And had I ranked a little higher, I wanted the Corps of Engineers.
And I think the Corps of Engineers quota went down to about 56, because everybody didn't select the Corps of Engineers.
But you got your, you selected your branch of service by how you ranked.
The number of guys ranked number one, he got his choice.
Ranked number two, number three, and on down to 66.
Well, then I had to select the Coastal Artillery.
I selected the Coastal Artillery as my choice, except
Then you had to wait two years after you graduated from the Military Academy to transfer to the Corps of Engineers.
So I said, well, I'll just take the Air Corps because I did pass the physical.
And then that'll be one year while you learn to fly, and then you just have one more year to wait until you could
go to the Corps of Engineers.
And of course I was basically I'm sure back to the architectural construction type of business that I was really interested in.
And then I passed the physical exam so everybody who passed the physical exam could come to the flying school.
And of course
The flying school is a great equalizer as far as people are concerned because some of them, about 50% of them, graduated from flying school and 50% didn't.
And so when you graduate from the flying school,
I would say that a very small proportion, I don't know exactly what it would be, but I would say certainly less than 25% of the officer corps were military graduates.
You mean West Point graduates?
Yeah, West Point graduates.
And the rest of them were from Texas A&M, et cetera.
And I know in the Air Force you really didn't look to see
Of course you knew who your classmates were and of course, but very seldom were you ever stationed with your classmates.
Most of the people that you had around you were non-graduates of the military academy.
They were graduates of Texas A&M or almost any college.
And you very seldom run into
any animosity between graduates and non-graduates.
I think probably General Powers, who commanded SAC later, when I was in SAC in 56, 57, 58, did I run into the fact that he objected to military academy graduates.
He was a non-military graduate.
But otherwise, I don't think it affected you at all.
Because I've heard from some A&M graduates that a West Point graduate is more conceited, more haughty.
And just for a couple of years, they were more clannish.
And for a couple of years, it was
rather difficult to get along, if you were both second lieutenants, to get along with a West Point man.
Now after that, they say it doesn't seem to make much difference.
What do you think about that?
Well, I think really your problem there is that when you graduate from the Kelly and arrive at your
first base at, say, Fort Island, Luke Field.
Of course, you have about five or maybe five people who report in at the same time.
You know them.
You've been talking to them for the last five years, four years or five years.
Your classmates that
arrived at Randolph and went to the same class with you at Randolph and Kelly, of course you've only known them for one year.
And I think normally and naturally why you talk and you congregate with the people that you've known so long.
And they've been your friends for that long.
But after that, why...
Well, by 1940, a lot of times I would be the only West Point graduate on the base.
I would have saved 400 officers.
I don't know.
In your opinion, which institution, A&M or West Point, produces a better caliber of officer?
Well, I would say it's really hard to say.
I would say it's really hard to say.
I think it really depends upon the individual.
I think it really depends on the individual as to how he reacts to situations.
The units that I commanded the air divisions by
You couldn't really distinguish between a Texas A&M graduate and a West Point graduate.
Would you say the same thing as far as which institution produces a leader, that it depends more on the individual?
I would say it really depends on the individual.
I don't really think West Point makes a leader.
I mean, I think they're too regimented.
I think they're really very regimentated.
as far as they do all the thinking for you.
Whereas I think that if you probably get more thinkers that attend outside colleges.
Does A&M make leaders?
Well, I don't think that through your college years that you really produce any leaders.

I really don't think that, I think it's really after you get out of college, maybe the course is, well it's very difficult to, in a classroom of descriptive geometry or chemistry, say this guy's going to be a leader and this guy's not going to be a leader.
There's no way of distinguishing.
All you're doing is teaching a guy how to think.
OK. Now, not only are we talking about two different types of institutions that produces officers.
We've been talking about West Point.
We've been talking about the core schools like Texas A&M.
And of course, we could also mention VMI and Virginia Tech.
What about the ROTC schools?
What about all the other land grant schools that have ROTC programs?
What did you think of the caliber of those ROTC graduates?
Well, I really never had an opportunity to compare.

You really don't think of, when you look at Captain Joe Blow, whether or not he's a graduate of Texas A&M or SMU or Houston or wherever they have an ROTC program, you really look at him as an individual.
and whether or not he's willing to accept responsibility and whether or not he's a pusher or whether or not he's a follower or whatever.
So you really don't sit down and compare individuals.
Now, in my master's thesis, I made a study of 100
commanders, base commanders, wing commanders, division commanders, as to the type of education that they had.
What did you find?
Well, you found that about a third of them didn't have any college education at all.
And yet they had been selected by somebody as being a commander.
And I made a study of
on whether or not they had graduated from a professional school in the military, whether or not the Air Command Staff School, Air War College, National War College, Industrial College.
And again, a third of them had been to no professional school in the Air Force, 34 percent.
What did you conclude?
Well, I concluded that
Well, it's hard to conclude anything, really.

You look at the graduates of the National War College, one of the individuals who was selected for attending the National War College, and only about 2% of the officer corps were going to attend the National War College.
Normally, as I remember, about 60% of those became a general officer.
But see, you were selecting the top, theoretically, the top 2% of the officer corps anyway to go to school.
So a large percentage of them normally would go.
High probability that they would go.
That they would go.
And I really think that you really don't have to go to college
to become a military leader.
I think you just have to have that knack of handling people and being able to have ideas and be decisive and get willing to rock the boat.
So as far as comparing graduates
various colleges.
I don't think it, I don't think you really, I really had an opportunity to look at each individual.
You did make an interesting statement though.
You said that men at West Point were not as, did you say not as likely to have ideas as ROTC graduates or something like something to that extent?
Well, during your college years at West Point, I would say that now I'm going to understand they've changed the curriculum now so that you have a lot of choice.
When I went there, you didn't have a choice.
You just took this course and out of this book, and this is the way it's to be taught.
And you didn't...
didn't even read a newspaper.
So to me why you learn a lot more in going to school and decide what courses you're going to take and how you're going to make the money to go to college.
And I would say that
would certainly improve your ability to make a success, whether or not it's in the military or whether or not it's in civilian life.
Many times, let's change the topic for a minute.
Many times I've read quite a bit on military history, especially journalists, other people who report on the military talk about what they call the military mentality.
There's a military way to do things.
Is there such a thing as a military mentality?
Well, in the military you have, and in government,
You have a tremendous amount of regulations to follow.
And your military mentality really is controlled by military regulations.
And you really don't have an opportunity to try new things.
that is not in accordance with the rules and regulations.
Okay, okay.
So you get in, you're regimented in that way.
In other words, what you would define as a military mentality is more regimentation, or more narrow maybe?
It's more controlled.
Once you get up into your more responsible jobs, not that you are limited to ways of doing things.

when I went to Sioux Falls, South Dakota to establish a radio school up there, you really, you could freewheel all you wanted to as long as you stayed within the budget and you could come up with all kinds of ideas on how to build mock-ups for various radio circuits and you could go out and establish
a collection center for all of the old radios in the state of South Dakota and North Dakota and Minnesota and Wisconsin and bring them in, tear them up and that type of thing was encouraged.
Exactly what you taught in the schools using the teaching methods that you had developed
was pretty well set down by a bunch of educators, of which I was one, I guess.
That you have a big seminar and decide on almost a day-to-day basis what is to be taught.
And I think it has to be.
If you're going to teach 14,000 students,
In 16 weeks, a radio course that you come out of the profession, you have to do, it has to be done on a day-to-day basis.
And you want those men to have similar training so they can communicate when they get out in the field.
That's right.
Let's talk about your graduation.
Graduated from West Point right in the middle of the Great Depression.
Wonderful.
Wonderful that you had a job.
Yeah, that's just exactly what I was going to ask.
I bet you were quite happy to have a job at that time.
Happy to have a job.
We had a ten percent pay cut as a cycle lieutenant, but it didn't bother me.
And I bought a 1930 Ford Roadster for two hundred dollars when I graduated.
1930 Ford Roadster, and I bought it when I graduated in 1933.
Oh, in 1933.
So you bought a pretty new car for a young man to have during the Depression.
Yeah, for $200, and I drove it home.
No, I would say it was very nice to have a job.
And talking to my classmates at
at Texas A&M who graduated then in 32, why so many of them didn't have a job.
Very few of them had jobs.
They went out and sold apples on the corners and things of that sort.
I think in talking to them is where you really have a story as to how they
progressed from the apple cart up to a wholesale grocery company or something of this sort.
There were a lot of successful people in that class of 32.
Now, what was your first assignment as a second lieutenant?
At Randolph, the flying school.
Okay, can you tell me about that?
Well, reported in and of course

I really wasn't real concerned about learning to fly, whether or not I graduated or not graduated, to learn to fly or not fly, because I was going to transfer to the engineers anyway, so I guess I just relaxed.
The people, some of the boys who had been looking forward since they were ten years old to be a pilot,
they just washed out because they just froze up and what have you.
But I didn't have any problem of learning to fly.
Of course your mechanical engineering part of studying engines and aerodynamics and weather and all the ground schools, I was pretty well duck soup.
That was no problem for you?
No problem, no.
and I went to Kelly and went through bombardment, which was, at that time we were flying Keystone bombers, a two-engine airplane, and that was my type.
I wanted to pursue, I was a conservative type and I liked the bombardment.
So I had no problem at all of learning to fly and of course
Once you learn to fly I guess it's just like being a gambler or being an alcoholic or something else.
It gets in your blood and I just stayed with it.
Now this is not the exact time but fairly close to the Billy Mitchell problem.
Do you remember that?
